courses.learning_outcomes:
1. To master the principle of electron microscopes;
2. To know the basic instrumentation of conventional electron microscope, and master the basic sample preparation methods;
3. To master the basic knowledge of crystalline symmetry and group theory;
4. To understand the theory of electron diffraction;
5. To master the methods for the interpretation of crystal symmetry through electron diffraction patterns;
6. To understand the principle of dark field/bright field imaging;
7. To understand the theory of high-resolution electron microscopy;
8. To master data analysis skill of high resolution electron microscopy images;
9. To understanding energy dispersive x-ray, and master data analysis skills in identifying material composition;
10. To understand electron energy loss spectroscopy method in identifying material chemical composition and electronic structures;
11. To understand the state-of-the-art in situ techniques in monitoring dynamics of material structural/ compositional/ property changes;
12. To analyze, judge and solve realistic problems and cases using combinational approaches (including diffraction pattern, dark field/bright field images, high resolution image, EDX, EELS, etc.);
13. To develop an analytical mind towards materials characterization;
14. To master basic experimental skills in using electron microscopy based techniques for practical material analysis projects.

courses.course_syllabus:
Principles of electron scattering and basics of electron microscopy
Group theory and basics of crystal symmetry;
Electron diffraction and crystal symmetry interpretation from the reciprocal space; Comparison with x-ray diffraction;
Wave optics and imaging principle of electron microscopy;
Theory and interpretation of high-resolution electron microscopy;
Analytical electron energy microscopy techniques including energy dispersive x-ray (EDX), electron energy loss spectroscopy (EELS), and various state-of-the-art in situ microscopy techniques.

